<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / Defence giants go to battle stations for the Great Game: The
desire of BAe and GEC to win VSEL reflects a wider conflict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With British Aerospace and GEC mobilising for a tug of love over VSEL, the
submarine maker, the real battle has begun for the future of the UK defence
industry. The number of defence contractors is shrinking rapidly, and the
choices left to companies wishing to merge and cut their costs are narrowing
fast.
Competition over any defence company up for grabs is likely to be fierce.
BAe would apparently have liked to buy helicopter-maker Westland when GKN
bid earlier this year, had GKN not started with an almost unstoppable
shareholding.
Now the attention has switched from air to sea systems. BAe wants to be the
project manager which controls the key contracts in ships as well as
aircraft. GEC, tired of its role as a supplier to BAe, is keen to expand its
naval presence and become a larger full-scale project manager in its own
right.
VSEL will go to one or the other. GEC has the advantage of being able to bid
in cash, while BAe does not face the competition difficulty of owning two
shipyards. The proximity of two large naval contracts - a Pounds 2.5bn order
for Trafalgar hunter-killer submarines and a Pounds 500m order for landing
ships - could make VSEL an attractive proposition.
But Britain's other small defence contractors are on their guard. There is a
great deal of common ground between the mid-life refitting of nuclear
submarines, which will soon be done exclusively at Devonport in Plymouth,
and their construction.
It would make sense for whoever owns VSEL to own Devonport, which is due to
be privatised over the next 18 months, the same timescale on which the
Trafalgar order will be placed.
Land systems - tanks and armoured personnel carriers - are also spread among
a wide range of companies and could be rationalised, too.
Some deals may seem to create strange bedfellows. Yet in the absence of
pan-European mergers, companies are having to find their savings where they
can. Several of the large US deals, most notably Lockheed's merger with
Martin Marietta, have also brought together companies with little in common
but their defence interests.
Savings on central overheads and the ability to manage defence contracts and
ministries skilfully are the strongest arguments in favour of the deals.
Savings will be generated whichever company wins VSEL. Central overheads
will be reduced and design and marketing teams consolidated. There are also
management gains to be made. Project management in defence is a particularly
black art and one which BAe in particular has practised well.
If either BAe or GEC can teach VSEL how to become a risk-taking prime
contractor managing a Pounds 2.5bn fixed-price order for Trafalgar
submarines, then the merged companies, and the ministry of defence, should
benefit.
The endgame, however, leaves BAe and GEC staring awkwardly at each other
over the chessboard. Resolving the BAe-GEC issue is going to be the Great
Game of the next decade.
Editorial Comment, Page 25;
Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Aerospace.
    General Electric Co.
    VSEL Consortium.
</CO>
<XX>
