<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / Accountancy Column: Opening the books and limiting liability
 -Jim Kelly examines the ramifications for accountants of Peat Marwick's
move towards incorporation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The problem with the uncovering of secrets is that it often disappoints. One
of the big secrets in the accountancy profession is how much the partners at
the big firms earn. Thanks to KPMG Peat Marwick's historic decision to
support incorporation of its audit arm we are about to find out.
We will, I suspect, be disappointed. The independently audited accounts of
Peat Marwick Audit plc, or whatever it may be called, will probably reveal
earnings for partners of a modest kind. KPMG appears confident the figures
will not raise eyebrows.
What has caused a stir is its decision, if supported by its clients, to be
the first accountancy firm of any size to move away from the confidential
world of the partnership. Its declared aim is to limit the exposure of
partners to legal actions. Those in a partnership face joint and several
liability when, for example, an audited corporate client collapses.
Disclosure will draw back the veil on KPMG's business for both clients and
competitors. This is one of the penalties KPMG is prepared to pay to limit
liability. They are also prepared to reveal a full financial statement for
the rest of the business: a bold undertaking which has caught some
competitors on the wrong foot.
There are other penalties to partial incorporation. The increased tax burden
on partners in the company is not inconsequential - although the benefits of
partnership are not what they were and will diminish further. It is also
likely that all Peat's partners, both inside and outside the audit practice,
will share the financial burden.
So taxation and disclosure are the immediate penalties. KPMG, and its
clients, might also fear that the partnership ethos will be lost within the
corporate framework. KPMG's senior partner Colin Sharman has obviously
decided that his partners do not need the fear of liability as a spur to
commitment. Corporate management structures, after all, also have
advantages. Most large partnerships with international links have moved
toward a corporate structure.
KPMG's competitors are likely to see other disadvantages to partial
incorporation: after all, despite a lot of movement behind the scenes, none
of them looks likely to follow suit in the short term. There are certainly
doubts within KPMG itself, where there is some disquiet up to partner level,
and possibly beyond.
But the real problem with the KPMG option is that it does not solve the one
problem which threatens the very existence of some of the big firms  - the
explosion in claims against auditors under joint and several liability. In
1983 litigation as a proportion of audit costs for the eight largest firms
was 2.6%. In 1993 it was 8 per cent and rising.
In 1983 the six biggest firms faced three claims. In 1993 they faced 210
with 600 still open at the end of the year. In the past 10 years three out
of five corporate collapses resulted in action against the auditor.
Earlier this year the big eight, including Peat Marwick, put a submission to
the Department of Trade and Industry urging reform of Section 310 of the
Companies Act 1985 to allow the limitation of liability for auditors. The
report noted that: 'Incorporation of accounting firms does not provide an
effective solution.'
Incorporation does not tackle the heart of the problem because the company
can still be sued; in fact it can still be brought to destruction. Also
those partners directly involved in negligent work are still liable. Legal
advice about the extent of this liability is variable but crucial. For
example: Is the accountant who trained the auditor who produced negligent
work also liable? Is the immediate manager liable? Is the consultant liable?
If the American experience, in which the leading accountancy firms have
become Limited Liability Partnerships (LLP), provides any precedent, it is
that liability would be strictly limited.
Expert opinion on the question of liability in the LLPs points to the
conclusion that direct supervision would need to be proved to extend
liability.
In the British context it appears that KPMG believes the law would follow
similar reasoning. KPMG is also likely to see pursuit of partners in its
audit arm as the second option for claimants after they have tackled the
company.
Another problem with incorporation as a counter-balance to liability is that
the partners are not protected from prior actions against them lodged before
incorporation. This is enough in itself to take the icing off of the
corporate cake for most of the Big Six.
There are other disadvantages. Being first, KPMG will take most of the pain
and some of the costs for the rest of the profession. When it comes to
disclosing full financial results for the business KPMG will be under
pressure to have them independently audited - hardly an inviting option.
So why has KPMG taken the plunge? The reorganisation of a business is
usually either superficial, as in the case of the LLP's in the US, or
profoundly structural, in order to gain competitive advantage.
What has KPMG to gain from what appears to be a halfway house? After all,
the new audit arm will fit into KPMG's exisiting structure admirably.
Competitors muse that the production of full financial results for the audit
arm will allow KPMG to declare to major customers the strength of its
financial resources to meet future claims.
Transparency will also remove suspicion from fee negotiations. Mr Sharman
seems more than happy to face new customers with his company's results on
the table.
KPMG are canvassing clients on incorporation but reactions seem generally
positive. Alan Spall, finance director of ICI, gauges his views as 'neutral
to positive'. His concerns are over adequate capitalisation and maintainance
of standards.
KPMG has clearly won itself a head start on incorporation and a distinctive
image in a market place often seen as bland and anonymous. But the firm is
just as aware as its competitors that incorporation is not the final answer.
Another incomplete option, not available under British law, is the move in
the US towards LLPs. One leading partner admits that if the legislation was
available in the UK he would move to LLP status overnight. Registration in
the US costs Dollars 100 per partner.
Interestingly, one of the few requirements for LLP status is the need to
demonstrate that the partnership provides Dollars 1m of liability insurance
or Dollars 1m of funds set aside to meet claims. But here again partners are
still liable for commercial debts and direct negligence.
Given the absence of the LLP option in Britain, KPMG has taken the only
viable action left to a firm which wants to act now. There are those in the
profession who privately say that KPMG, in going for the audit incorporation
option, has damaged the campaign for reform of the law on liability. That
campaign is currently stalled while the government considers the
professions' call for legal reform.
Meanwhile accountants will continue to work in the shadow liability. Graham
Ward, a partner in Price Waterhouse, and chairman of the Institute of
Chartered Accountants' working group on liability, sees a 'fundamental
imbalance' in the economics of auditing, in which the risks do not match
rewards.
KPMG's initiative, while courageous and potentially astute if it captures
the imagination of clients, does little to redress that balance. It does,
however, promise to put more accountability into accounting.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>KPMG Peat Marwick.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
