<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Rifkind says fighting jobs
safe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cuts in the fighting strength of the armed forces are over, Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, the defence secretary, promised the conference yesterday.
The pledge, which signals that the Ministry of Defence will escape big cuts
in this year's public expenditure round, was cheered by delighted
constituency representatives.
Praising the performance of British troops in Bosnia, Northern Ireland and
Kuwait, Mr Rifkind said that future demands on the armed forces were
uncertain.
But he told the conference: 'I can give you this undertaking. Even if our
commitments were to reduce, there will be no contraction in the fighting
strength of our army.
'There will be no further cuts in battalions, no more amalgamations of
regular regiments.' Any reduction in commitments would 'not be a
justification for cuts in the armed services'. Rather, it would 'be good
news for them,' he said.
'It would mean more time for training, more opportunity for service abroad
and more time with their families. That is what the armed forces want to
hear.'
Later, Mr Rifkind said he was 'absolutely certain' that the Treasury would
not seek further cuts in the armed forces following the completion of the
Options for Change programme of efficiency savings. In a round of
interviews, Mr Rifkind said that his pledge not to cut the fighting strength
of the forces would last 'as long as this government is in office'.
Speaking on BBC television, he said: 'The Treasury has accepted that the
armed forces have more than made their (contribution) to the needs of the
taxpayer.
'While we will always be expected to find ways of being more efficient and
concerned with value for money . . . there will be no proposals put to me by
my colleagues for any cuts in the fighting strength of our armed forces.'
Mr Rifkind's pledge followed attacks on defence cost cutting by several
constituency representatives. Mr Bob Martin, a retired air commodore from
Oxford, was applauded as he criticised the 'Whitehall warriors' cutting the
forces. 'In the past year or two there have been more axes and knives
hacking away at our services by these new-style Whitehall warriors than the
forces have ever experienced.'
</TEXT>
