<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: High-risk Ulster vote may
be allowed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Tory leadership will decide today whether to allow a vote on an
amendment urging the government to be 'a persuader for the union' at the end
of this afternoon's conference debate on Northern Ireland, David Owen
writes.
The amendment has been promoted heavily by the party's grassroots members in
Northern Ireland. They have voiced concern at what they term the
government's 'neutrality' on the issue of Ulster's future status.
A decision to allow a vote would be a high-risk strategy as adoption of the
amendment could strain relations between London and Dublin.
The motion salutes the 'courage' shown by both Mr John Major and Mr Albert
Reynolds, the Irish prime minister, in agreeing the Downing Street
declaration, and urges ministers to leave no stone unturned in pursuing
peace 'consistent with the rights of the people of Northern Ireland to
determine by democratic means their future'.
In Bournemouth yesterday, Mr David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist MP for Upper
Bann, backed Mr Major's caution in responding to the IRA's open-ended
ceasefire.
</TEXT>
