<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Prospect of housing
benefit cut recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Peter Lilley is playing down speculation that his department will
introduce big cuts in housing benefit this year.
The social security secretary has told colleagues that his officials at the
Department of Social Security can make only 'cosmetic' changes to the
housing benefit programme, because they are occupied with too many
cost-cutting projects in next year's legislative timetable.
Treasury officials have put intense pressure on the DSS in recent months to
reduce its Pounds 9bn annual expenditure on housing benefit, arguing that
the programme is growing much faster than the nation's ability to pay for
it.
Earlier this year Mr Jonathan Aitken, chief secretary to the Treasury, said
he wanted to target housing benefit costs in this year's Budget, arguing
that 'quite a lot' of recipients were 'living in houses that are too big for
them'. He said: 'There are areas such as the exponential growth in housing
benefit where you have to look very carefully to make sure taxpayers' money
is not being wasted.'
However - as this year's public spending round draws to a close - officials
at the DSS have privately remarked that Mr Aitken was not properly briefed
when he made these remarks, and that the DSS cannot carry out a sweeping
reform of the programme this year.
They argue that large-scale changes to the programme would require primary
legislation and that the DSS is already committed to pushing through two
substantial bills next year on the reform of occupational pensions and the
Jobseeker's Allowance.
Mr Lilley confirmed yesterday that he would introduce a 'Back To Work' bonus
next year, making it worthwhile for unemployed people to take part-time work
as a prelude to starting a full-time job.
Under the proposals, which will benefit 150,000 people, those who lose
benefit when they start a part-time job will build up a DSS 'credit'. This
can be converted into a bonus of up to Pounds 1,000 when they undertake a
full-time job.
Mr Lilley told journalists that the government would shortly be introducing
a white paper on the Jobseeker's Allowance, outlining details of a new
agreement. This may tighten up the rules under which benefit recipients are
obliged to look for a job.
</TEXT>
