<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Heseltine pushes for
postal sell-off - Chief whip to have final say on privatisation go-ahead /
Backbench critics softening
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, yesterday sought to
steady government nerves on the proposed Royal Mail flotation in a
barnstorming conference speech extolling the benefits of privatisation.
Amid cabinet uncertainty about the government's ability to push
privatisation through the Commons, Mr Heseltine warned against caution and
urged the party to 'force the pace of change'.
Senior ministers say the cabinet will decide shortly whether to include a
Post Office privatisation bill in the Queen's Speech for the next
parliament, which starts in mid-November.
There is a small cabinet majority for Mr Heseltine's plan to float 51 per
cent of the Royal Mail, following the conversion of Mr Douglas Hurd, the
foreign secretary, who was sceptical but now believes privatisation is the
best option.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, has supported Mr Heseltine, as have
rightwing cabinet ministers such as Mr John Redwood, the Welsh secretary,
who yesterday strongly defended privatisation at a conference fringe
meeting.
However, the final decision will depend on a judgment by Mr Richard Ryder,
the chief whip, and Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, on the number of
Conservative backbench MPs who may defy the government and oppose the bill.
Mr Ryder is believed to be confident that the bill can be forced through, in
spite of the death yesterday of Mr John Blackburn, MP for Dudley West, which
reduces the government's majority to 14.
But senior ministers say no decisions will be made until further soundings
have been taken when MPs return to the Commons for the autumn 'spillover'
session next week. 'At the moment, the numbers don't look very good,' said
one.
There is some evidence of softening opposition among critics of
privatisation, following government assurances on universal delivery prices
and the future of rural post offices.
Mr David Nicholson, chairman of the West Country group of Conservative MPs,
many of whom remain unconvinced about the merits of privatisation, signalled
that some backbench critics were ready to be won over.
'If Mr Heseltine is to proceed with a partial privatisation and to get
second-reading support, the government will have to continue to explain, in
detail, why it is important for the industry,' he said.
Mr Heseltine, making his first conference speech since suffering a heart
attack last year, won a two-minute standing ovation for a wideranging speech
which demonstrated his continuing mastery of conference oratory.
Lauding the government's earlier privatisation achievements, he dismissed
'those who tell me that the best way for the Tories to win the next election
is to slow the pace, to ease the pressure, to opt for the quiet life'.
As representatives cheered, he told them: 'What the government is
considering and consulting about is how to allow the Royal Mail to be as
successful as British Telecom or British Airways.'
Mr Alan Johnson, general secretary of the UCW communications union, said in
Bournemouth that Mr Hesel-tine's failure to announce the go-ahead for
privatisation 'illustrates how deep-seated government fears are over the
future of our trusted and cherished Post Office'.
He said most Conservative party members 'seem aware that privatising and
breaking up the Post Office would not only be damaging and unnecessary but
also deeply unpopular'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
    P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
