<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: New conference darling
steps up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo yesterday set out a 'distinctive' Conservative agenda
for the 1996 European Union intergovernmental conference, as he threatened
to usurp the unofficial title of 'conference darling' from Mr Michael
Heseltine.
The rightwing employment secretary used a speech to the Thatcherite
Conservative Way Forward group on the conference fringe to set out the
'clear blue water' he saw between the Tories and Mr Tony Blair's new-look
Labour party. He made it clear that the adoption of more rightwing policies
was not the key to distinguishing the party from Labour.
'If Labour were to adopt every Conservative policy, if Labour were to
publish our manifesto word for word . . . there would still be a yawning
gulf between the two parties,' he said. 'A gulf of belief and principle: the
gulf between the rock of our philosophy and the quicksand of Labour's
posturing.'
In an impressive and well-judged display in a series of interviews and
speeches yesterday, Mr Portillo did not make any semblance of an overtly
disloyal remark. But those witnessing his performance could scarcely have
been in doubt about the underlying message: the young pretender was still
around and had reinforced his credentials as a likely rightwing challenger
in any future leadership contest.
The pains he took to appear restrained and statesmanlike were helped by
Monday's startling speech by Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor. By
comparison, Mr Portillo's message - even his forthright call in the
conference hall to 'stop the rot from Brussels' - seemed positively
mainstream.
Even so, he was careful not to provide ammunition for anyone anxious to
portray him as having stepped out of line.
He said he was pleased by the rapturous reception, complete with four-minute
standing ovation, that his conference speech received because 'the things
that got the biggest cheer . . . were the things that John Major had won for
the Conservative party'. And asked about the difference in tone between his
speech, with its stinging attack on Brussels bureaucracy, and that by Mr
Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, he said: 'Mr Hurd is in a different league
from me.'
Mr Portillo proposed a three-pronged agenda around which he said the
Conservative party could unite in the run-up to the 1996 intergovernmental
conference. This comprised: making sure most decisions affecting people's
daily lives were taken by national governments; encouraging the European
Union to be 'outward looking' in its approach to trade and new members; and
resisting moves to impose new costs on business that would impair the
competitiveness of European companies.
In a wide-ranging and combative speech, he was restrained enough to sidestep
a question on whether he would rescind the Maastricht treaty and said Mr
Major was right to delay a decision on joining a single currency.
Mr Portillo's performance came as Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, warned
Mr Blair that he would play into Tory hands if he chose to 'fight on our
ground'. In a vigorous defence on the conference fringe of free enterprise
and individual action, Mr Howard said there was still 'a philosophical gulf'
between the two main parties.
'The values and vision of the Conservative party are as powerful and
resonant as they were in 1979,' he said. 'We believe free markets and strong
communities complement each other.'
</TEXT>
