<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / Pounds 100m boost planned for retail centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chelsfield, the property company led by Mr Elliott Bernerd, yesterday sought
planning permission from Dudley Borough Council in the West Midlands to
undertake a Pounds 100m expansion of the Merry Hill shopping centre.
The 650,000 sq ft expansion at what is already one of the four largest
shopping centres in Britain would be the biggest retail development in the
UK since the property industry moved into recession during 1990.
Its announcement follows declarations by Mr John Gummer, the environment
secretary, that new shopping centres outside towns are unacceptable. He has
reiterated the government's policy of sustaining the vitality of existing
town centres.
Merry Hill, on the west side of the Birmingham-Black Country conurbation,
was developed during the 1980s with the help of tax concessions. It is on
land to which the government gave enterprise zone status after the closure
of a steelworks.
Chelsfield, the leading member of a consortium which bought Merry Hill from
the receivers of Mountleigh, a failed property company, last year, is
consolidating its control of the shopping centre.
It is paying Pounds 27m to lift its stake in the consortium, MH Holdings, to
90 per cent from 50 per cent, and expects to buy the other 10 per cent next
January. The seller is a group of private Saudi Arabian investors.
Disclosure of the plans to expand the centre, which has 1.4m sq ft of shops,
excluding retail warehouses, follows discussions between Chelsfield and the
local authority, and reflects the assumption that planning permission will
be granted.
The council, which opposed the original development, fearing the loss of
trade at the traditional centres of Dudley and Stourbridge, is supporting
the expansion.
The local authority's attitude to the development has changed for three
reasons:
The expansion, based on a new department store and extensive catering
facilities, could provide 2,000 jobs.
Chelsfield is establishing training facilities so that local residents can
take up the jobs.
The company has agreed to spend Pounds 8.25m on investment projects in the
borough. This includes Pounds 1.5m on road improvements - access to Merry
Hill through highly populated districts is difficult.
Chelsfield yesterday sought to head off any objections by adopting Mr
Gummer's line on opposition to out-of-town shopping centres. It argued that,
with its adjacent hotel and office developments, the development is akin to
a traditional town centre.
It noted that Merry Hill is not on the edge of, but inside the conurbation
and that 15 per cent of its 25m customers a year arrive on foot or on public
transport.
Further, Chelsfield said, expansion is directed more at persuading existing
customers to stay longer than to attracting new visitors.
</TEXT>
