<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / US details Cuba refugee plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US yesterday announced long-awaited details of its plan to issue visas
to 20,000 Cubans, promised as part of an agreement with the Castro regime
last month. A State Department spokeswoman said the government would expand
the criteria for refugee status, review previously denied refugee cases and
make visas immediately available to unmarried children of Cubans already
issued immigrant visas or granted refugee status. The government would
operate a lottery that 'will substantially broaden avenues of legal
migration for all Cubans, including those without direct family ties to the
US'. The new visa programmes would be available to Cubans now in Cuba. Those
in safe havens at the US naval base in Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, and in Panama
would be told about the programmes but must return home in order to
participate.
