FT  13 OCT 94 / Panama agrees to take Cedras
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER and TED BARDACKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PANAMA, PORT-AU-PRINCE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Panama yesterday agreed to take in Lieutenant-General Raoul Cedras, the
leader of Haiti's military coup who relinquished power on Monday. He was
expected in Panama last night just three days before the scheduled return of
exiled president Jean-Bertrand Aristide. A senior Panamanian official said:
'We received a faxed letter this afternoon from President Aristide asking
Panama to accept Cedras and we have agreed.' All day yesterday, US military
forces mounted guard on the home of the ousted general as removal vans
loaded with his possessions headed towards aircraft awaiting him at the
capital city's airport. A US embassy spokesman said that the chief coup
strategist, General Pillipe Biamby, was likely to accompany his colleague
into exile. Gen Cedras's departure follows the collapse of the government
led by de facto president Emile Jonassaint, who left the presidential palace
on Tuesday. All of Mr Jonassaint's ministers also abandoned their offices,
and US troops peacefully secured 15 different government buildings. Inside
the presidential palace, US security officers and Mr Aristide's transition
team began initial preparations to receive the legitimate president when he
arrives on Saturday.
