<HEADLINE>
FT  13 OCT 94 / Israeli kidnap puts peace in jeopardy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By A CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israeli-Palestinian reconciliation was facing its gravest test last night
over the kidnapping by Hamas extremists of an Israeli soldier.
Israel's prime minister, Mr Yitzhak Rabin, made clear that he was holding Mr
Yassir Arafat, the PLO chairman, personally responsible for the fate of
19-year-old Nachshon Waxman. The soldier was kidnapped close to Ben-Gurion
airport outside Tel Aviv on Sunday, and is believed by Israel to be held in
the Palestinian autonomous area of the Gaza Strip.
Responsibility has been claimed by the military wing of Hamas. Announcing on
Tuesday that they were holding Mr Waxman, the kidnappers have said they will
kill him tomorrow unless Israel releases dozens of Palestinian prisoners,
including the Hamas leader Sheikh Ahmad Yassin.
The crisis marks a moment of truth in the Israel-Palestinian autonomy
process, with Hamas clearly seeking to derail the peace accords, undermine
Mr Arafat's authority in the occupied territories, and provoke greater
opposition inside Israel to the moderate Rabin government.
Adamantly opposed to any accommodation with Israel, Hamas already appears to
have achieved some of its objectives. Israel has suspended negotiations in
Cairo with the PLO on the next stages of the autonomy process, and fuelled
further discontent among Gaza's Palestinian labour force by clamping a
closure order on the Strip that prevents workers travelling to Israel.
Mr Rabin spoke several times by telephone to Mr Arafat yesterday, urging a
search, and telling him that he regarded the crisis as a 'true test' of
relations.
A PLO official, who asked not be named, said Palestinian security forces
were due to begin arresting Hamas activists last night in an effort to
discover the whereabouts of the soldier.
'The Supreme Security Council of the Palestinian Authority has taken a
decision to continue investigations and searching for the captive soldier. .
. More extreme measures also will be taken whereby a wave of arrests of
Hamas activists will start. . . until the Palestinian (self-rule) Authority
arrives at the truth as to how he was kidnapped and where he is,' the
official said.
Israeli ministers said that, were the kidnapping to end in Mr Waxman's
death, there could be serious consequences for the future of the autonomy
process. 'If the autonomous areas turn into a shelter for murders,' said Mr
Amnon Rubinstein, education minister, 'Israel cannot be expected to expand
those areas'.
Interviewed on Israeli television last night, Sheikh Yassin urged the
kidnappers not to kill Mr Waxman. 'It would serve no purpose,' he said. 'Our
religion requires us to keep him alive and treat him well.'
Mr Arafat condemned the kidnapping and held a rare meeting with Hamas
leaders. Several of his spokesmen issued statements denying the soldier was
being held in Gaza. This denial was echoed by Hamas. 'We strongly deny the
kidnapped soldier is in the autonomous areas,' said a telephone caller
speaking on behalf of Hamas' military.
Yesterday, the kidnappers released a video showing Mr Waxman, who holds dual
US-Israeli citizenship, and who was conscripted six months ago, pleading for
his freedom. Looking dazed but controlled, he urged the government to meet
his captors' demands.
The Hamas militants also took credit for a shooting spree in central
Jerusalem on Sunday, during which two people were killed and more than a
dozen injured before the gunmen were themselves slain.
Mr Nabil Sha'ath, head of the PLO delegation to the suspended autonomy talks
in Cairo, said last night that it was 'unfair' of Israel to have broken off
the negotiations.
Israeli officials made clear that the talks had been postponed rather than
called off.
</TEXT>
