<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Equities surge stimulated by
solid earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices surged yesterday as solid earnings news brought sharp gains
to stocks across the board, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 55.51 higher at 3,876.83, a little
lower than its session best. The index was held back by the triggering of
NYSE restrictions on program-guided buying. The so-called 'downtick"rule
went into effect at mid-morning, when the Dow pushed past more than 50
points higher than its opening mark.
The rally was broad based, as reflected in the Standard &amp; Poor's 500, up
6.75, or 1.5 per cent, at 465.79. On the NYSE, advancing issues were leading
declines by about a three-to-one margin on heavy volume of 355m shares.
The Nasdaq composite also staged a powerful advance, gaining 8.76 to 765.57.
The American SE composite, up 1.78 at 457.76, lagged behind.
It was the third day in a row in which stocks showed marked improvement. The
sustained upturn reflected an easing of concerns over an immediate move by
the Federal Reserve to lift short-term interest rates.
The rally was given added impetus yesterday by a published report, quoting
unnamed Fed officials, which suggested that policy makers would wait until
their next scheduled meeting on November 15 before tightening credit
conditions again.,
The shift in sentiment, which had begun when Friday's employment data proved
to be weaker than expected, was quite evident in the Treasury market, where
bond prices made further progress ahead of this week's inflation news.
Meanwhile, equity investors had a smorgasbord of appealing corporate results
from which to feast. PepsiCo gained Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 34 3/4 after
beating the consensus forecast with net earnings of 68 cents a share.
Motorola led the technology sector after revealing impressive quarterly
results after the close of trading the previous session. Its shares were
marked up Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 54 with an upgrading by Merrill Lynch
giving the stock added support.
Digital Equipment forged Dollars 1 1/4 ahead to Dollars 29 1/2 on news that
it had sold another of its marginal businesses.
Chrysler was the first of the Big Three car makers to report, but the
response to its announcement was restrained, even though its performance was
better than most had predicted. The issue added Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 46
5/8 .
International Paper's results were a disappointment, and its stock, down
Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 77 1/2 , was one of only two Dow industrial
components to lose ground.
Several other cyclical stocks were up sharply as investors anticipated good
news to come. Caterpillar gained Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 55 1/2 , General
Electric was up Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 48 1/4 and Deere jumped Dollars 2
3/8 to Dollars 70 7/8 .
There was something more tangible to boost confidence in Procter &amp; Gamble,
up Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 62 1/4 . Its chairman told shareholders that the
company had just completed its best quarter ever.
Biogen backtracked a further Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 50. The company fell
victim to profit-taking for a second day even though it had revealed that
clinical trials for beta interferon, a multiple sclerosis treatment, were
successful.
</TEXT>
<XX>
