<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / International Company News: Intel seeks to stop shipments of
AMD chips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Intel is seeking an injunction to force rival Advanced Micro Devices to halt
shipments of microprocessor chips, following a US court ruling that a small
element of the 'microcode' contained in AMD's 486 microprocessors infringes
Intel copyright.
Intel said AMD must immediately stop making and selling the chips, which are
used in personal computers. AMD, however, said that in anticipation of an
injunction it had already begun production this week of chips with the
infringing microcode expunged. It said it did not expect any disruption to
shipments of its 486 microprocessors to PC manufacturers.
'This litigation is simply another effort by Intel to limit competition in
the 486 microprocessor market,' said Mr W. J. Sanders III, AMD chairman and
chief executive officer. 'It must not succeed.'
The copyright dispute is the latest development in almost a decade of legal
battles between Intel, the world's largest chip maker, and AMD, its former
technology partner. AMD sells microprocessors that emulate Intel's designs.
The copyright infringement ruling covers a very small portion of a
microprocessor microcode used for in-circuit emulation, or debugging of
software. AMD said the code was 'superfluous'.
The ruling applies only to this portion of microcode and 'does not affect
jury verdicts returned earlier this year upholding AMD's right to
manufacture and sell microchips containing Intel microcode', AMD said.
Intel charged, however, that AMD had deliberately used Intel microcode.
Being 'compatible with Intel technology was so critical to AMD's strategy
that AMD copied the ICE code, after it had specifically given up any rights
to do so', said Mr F. Thomas Dunlap, Intel vice-president and general
counsel.
AMD will ask the court for 'reasonable time to change our production lines',
said Mr Sanders. The production cycle for microprocessors is about 12 weeks,
so it will be several weeks before the new chips are available. AMD will
also have to destroy up to 100,000 chips that it has in inventory, Mr
Sanders said.
AMD expects to ship between 1m and 1.2m microprocessors in the current
quarter. 'While we are not giving up our rights to appeal, we are looking at
the decision as final,' said Mr Sanders.
</TEXT>
<XX>
