<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / International Company News: UAP slides 22% to FFr853m in
first half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Union des Assurances de Paris, one of France's largest insurance groups,
yesterday reported consolidated profits down 22 per cent to FFr853m (Dollars
161.55m) in the first six months of the year.
Consolidated insurance income rose 14 per cent, or 9 per cent on a
like-for-like basis, to FFr81bn, including a contribution from non-life
business of FFr42.9bn.
The figures included a substantial charge triggered by a jump in goodwill
amortisation to FFr509m in the six months to June 30, against FFr384m in the
first half last year.
Mr Jacques Friedman, chairman, said the year-end results should be improved
over those of last year, but admitted that they would not increase 'to the
extent of the objectives we had set ourselves in very different conditions a
few months ago'.
He said the accounts showed a 'favourable trend in technical insurance
conditions', which he believed were likely to be replicated in the second
half of the year. He highlighted expanded activity, improved technical
results and productivity gains.
However, he cautioned about the uncertainty caused by current economic
conditions, and said that the decline in the results was triggered by a
deterioration of the financial and property markets.
Premium income generated outside France represented 65 per cent of the total
for the first half of the year. Overall, the company said there was an
improvement in non-life insurance technical conditions and in the
claims/premium ratio.
It said worsening property and financial markets had led to greater property
provisions in subsidiaries now under the control of UAP, UAP Vie and UAP
Incendie Accident.
Banque Worms, its banking subsidiary, incurred a loss of FFr394m for the
first half, lower than budgeted and dragging down overall banking results
for the UAP group to FFr438m from FFr4362m.
</TEXT>
