<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Vincent Hanna is one of the best informed, most relaxed, and (crucially
important) funny political journalists on television. The only trouble is
that he tends to recognise this better than anyone. Still, A Week In
Politics is just about the best political programme we have, and A Year In
Politics, the title chosen for the annual party conference programmes, is
particularly good. Hanna has considerable success in convincing his guests
that it is so late at night on a minority channel (12.10 C4) that nobody
will be watching and they can therefore let their hair down and say anything
they like. He, and consequently his viewers, had a wonderful time at
Blackpool last week: will the Tories also do us proud in Bournemouth?
Earlier, BBC1 screens the last episode in the first series of Common As
Muck, William Ivory's drama about dustmen. He has managed to plait the theme
of impending privatisation quite successfully with the other strands of the
men's lives (9.30). Another council employee, rat-catcher Paul Taylor, holds
the camera for Video Diaries, telling us of his anti-Nazi activities (9.30
BBC2).
</TEXT>
