<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Mortgage lending sinks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Total mortgage lending fell sharply last month compared with August,
emphasising the fragile nature of the housing market recovery, Barclays Bank
said yesterday.
The bank said in a survey that solicitors' home-loan transactions indicated
that gross new mortgage advances in England fell 7 per cent last month
compared with August.
The figures reflected the completion of loans negotiated in early and
mid-summer before last month's rise of half a percentage point in interest
rates.
Mr Garry Skelton, head of Barclays mortgage lending, said: 'It is too early
to judge the impact of the rate rise, but it does not augur well for October
lending. For most people increases in monthly mortgage repayments have yet
to take effect.'
He said the bank had seen a sharp increase in demand for fixed-rate
mortgages since the rise, but mortgage applications overall last month were
about the same level as in August.
'Traditionally we would expect mortgage applications to increase in
September and October but, for one reason or another, this has not happened
during the past few years,' said Mr Skelton.
Barclays blamed uncertainty about job prospects and the economy as well as
tax and fixed-rate mortgage rises earlier in the year for the decline in
mortgage completions since August - even though completions last month were
9 per cent higher than September last year.
The biggest fall was in Greater London where mortgage lending fell 10.6 per
cent compared with August and 7.6 per cent compared with September last
year. Only the south-west region saw an increase in lending - of 5.6 per
cent compared with August.
'Overall housing market activity appears largely to be concentrated among
first-time buyers, new properties and at the upper end of the market,' said
Mr Skelton.
House prices have remained static since the third quarter of last year
according to a survey published today by Halifax Building Society. Regions
showing the strongest growth in prices over the period were Northern Ireland
(+9 per cent), Scotland (+3.4 per cent), Greater London (+1.8 per cent) and
south-east England (+1.6 per cent).
