<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Shake-up urged for cathedrals
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Church of England's cathedrals should be more professional in attracting
visitors and selling themselves, the Archbishops' Commission of Cathedrals
said yesterday.
The commission said better financial planning and management was crucial to
the running of the 42 cathedrals, which were failing to make best use of
resources.
It urged the abolition of the freehold for future cathedral clergy posts,
ending the 'job-for-life' policy. But it warned against 'slavish adoption of
business techniques' and said decisions on entry charges must be left to
individual cathedrals.
The commission, chaired by Lady Howe, recommended wide-ranging reform of
cathedral government in order to help achieve greater openness and
accountability.
The report, Heritage and Renewal, rejected suggestions that cathedrals were
in crisis. It endorsed their role as 'the seat of the bishop and a centre of
worship and mission'.
The compilers of the document admitted that long-standing organisational
arrangements failed to meet contemporary needs - and suggested a simple
framework for future governance.
Under the proposals each cathedral would be governed by a council with
members drawn from people with different interests in the institution. The
diocesan bishop would chair the council and an outside administrator would
head a four-person administrative team which would include lay people.
The study also called for better training for cathedral clergy, lay staff
and volunteers - and urged the creation of a commission to offer advice on
best practice.
Lady Howe said yesterday the commission had found that cathedrals were 'in
good heart, but in need of significant change'. The review, the first of its
kind for 70 years, 'did not propose a break or discontinuity with the past,
but rather organic change and development'.
The Church of England's cathedrals were among the 'spiritual and
architectural glories' of the nation, she added. But while worship and music
were 'generally superb', the picture was 'less satisfactory' elsewhere and
the governance of cathedrals was 'complex and confusing'.
Lady Howe said: 'Overall, the finances of cathedrals, while not in jeopardy,
are less than comfortable. There is scope, too, for improved financial
planning and management. There is also considerable variation between
cathedrals in the performance of their trading and visitor activities.'
The commission wanted to see a cut in legal red tape and clearer, more
precise management arrangements.
</TEXT>
