<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Loyalty of readers to newspapers is questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Newspaper readers are far less loyal to individual titles than previously
thought, Taylor Nelson AGB, the market research group, said.
Even before steep cuts in the prices of The Sun and The Times there was far
more movement in newspaper readership than previously supposed, said the
group.
'Far from newspapers being a stable market, it is highly turbulent,' Mr
Stephan Buck, a director of Taylor Nelson AGB, said yesterday.
The company surveyed loyal newspaper readers in June last year, before the
price war started, and in March this year. The Daily Telegraph and Daily
Mirror both gained 15 per cent of new loyal readers over the period, but
lost 24 per cent. The cut-price Times lost 35 per cent of its previously
loyal readers but gained 64 per cent, giving a net increase of 29 per cent
in the period.
Mr Buck believes that, even though official Audit Bureau of Circulation and
National Readership Survey figures might show no significant net gains or
losses, newspapers could still lose and gain about 20 per cent of their
'loyal' readership in a year.
'No wonder heavy price-cutting brought in significant numbers of new regular
purchasers, just as it would in any other fast-moving consumer goods
market,' Mr Buck said.
The research was based on the Taylor Nelson AGB Mediaspan system which
regularly monitors the purchases of a panel of 8,500 households.
A different project by RSGB, part of Taylor Nelson AGB, found the highest
level of readership commitment was to The Guardian and the lowest broadsheet
commitment was to The Independent and The Times.
Healds, the convenience-store chain in north-west England, is selling
newspapers at half price until Christmas.
