<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Regulator lays down rules for train operators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The rules for train operating companies seeking to negotiate access to the
railway network owned by Railtrack were set out yesterday by Mr John Swift
QC, the rail regulator.
The handbook sets criteria for agreeing the details of timetables,
performance incentives and track maintenance standards. It sets great store
by open competition and flexible contracts.
The guidelines have emerged from talks between the train operators and
Railtrack and will be applied to future negotiations as the operators move
into the private sector.
The aim is to ensure that agreements are reached which protect the interests
of travellers; promote the development of the rail network; and enable
companies providing railway services to plan for the future.
Issues on which the document sets rules include:
Access agreements must be flexible enough to allow for effective railway
operations without the need continually to consult the regulator. But they
should not allow agreements which deliberately flout the regulator's
intentions.
Agreements must contain a 'reopener provision' to allow changes to be made
to, for example, franchise periods and levels of charges, when the regulator
publishes policy statements in November and April.
Timetables which make it difficult for Railtrack to franchise routes to
other operators would be subject to very close scrutiny.
Railtrack will be expected to show that it has plans to renew track which
matches the sums it sets aside for depreciation in its accounts. Agreements
must also include clauses which provide an incentive to Railtrack to improve
the performance of the track network.
Railtrack and the train operators must negotiate agreements which compensate
the train operators if maintenance work takes longer than planned and they
are unable to use the track.
Train operators will be expected to adopt flexible computer networks which
do not tie them into expensive and inappropriate systems.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Railtrack.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
