<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Staff at ITV station given notice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yorkshire-Tyne Tees Television last night began issuing dismissal notices to
employees who have not unconditionally accepted new terms and conditions
designed to cut the company's costs.
The company's letter, giving notice of termination of contract, said
employees who had not signed their agreement to the new terms were not
required to work their notice period, but would be re-instated if they
agreed to the new conditions.
Unions insisted the company was acting unlawfully and advised members not to
be forced into signing.
But the company said its actions were consistent with 'eminent legal advice'
and wholly within the law. 'More importantly they are designed to secure the
future of the company and all those who want to continue working with us.
'Security of employment for staff and a competitive company operation cannot
not be achieved without abandoning some of the practices of the eighties.'
The issue, it said, was one of realism. 'If after further consideration
there are still those who do not accept our proposals to secure the future,
we can only look upon their departure with regret.'
The company declined to say how many of its 800 employees had signed.
The notices of termination sent out last night were to Yorkshire employees.
The 200 Tyne Tees employees face a deadline of 4pm today.
The company, whose employees work an annualised hours system, wants to scrap
premium rate overtime payments, and pay additional hours at flat rate. The
unions say this would mean some employees' earnings would drop by up to 40
per cent. They say the changes would also scrap safeguards agreed when
annualised hours were introduced.
Unions at the company are talking legal advice on their next move. Mr Colin
Bourne, the National Union of Journalists' northern region organiser, said
the law defined the dismissals as redundancies.
'People now have the right to claim damages for breach of contract, to claim
unfair dismissal and payment in lieu of the period for which the company is
legally required to consult with the unions,' he said.
</TEXT>
