<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Pools win jackpot concessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday spelled out concessions to football pools
operators, including a partial right to rollover jackpots when there is no
outright winner.
The number of jackpots the football pools operators will be able to roll
over will, however, be dictated by the number of rollovers in the National
Lottery which will be launched next month.
It is believed that the Department of National Heritage argued for such
limits to protect the lottery from pools competition.
When there is no overall winner in the National Lottery and the main prize,
which could be about Pounds 2m, is rolled over to the following week, the
pools companies get a 'rollover credit'.
If there is no pools jackpot winner the pools companies can use the credit
to roll over the weekly jackpot - up to Pounds 750,000 for Vernons and
Pounds 2m for Littlewoods - within a six-month time limit.
Mr Malcolm Hughes, managing director of Vernons, said last night: 'Obviously
we are delighted at the movement in the direction of liberalising the rules.
It is still not the complete deregulation we anticipated when rollovers were
promised.'
The order bringing the changes into effect also reduces the age limit for
those able to play the football pools from 18 to 16.
Newsagents, shops and betting offices will also be able to act as agents for
the pools companies for the first time.
Pools companies will be watching to see what effect the launch of the
National Lottery has on their business and may yet return to the government
to seek further concessions.
Mr Michael Forsyth, Home Office minister, said yesterday that the right to
hand football coupons in to local retail outlets 'will provide the small
shop with the chance to benefit from an extra source of revenue'.
National Lottery tickets will be available at about 10,000 outlets at its
launch, a network that will grow to more than 35,000.
</TEXT>
