<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Corporate member to sit on Lloyd's ruling body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first representative of the new corporate investors in Lloyd's of London
has been elected to the insurance market's rulemaking and disciplinary
council.
Mr Jonathan Agnew's unopposed election marks a further rise in the influence
of corporate capital at Lloyd's - as opposed to individual Names whose
assets have traditionally supported the market.
Mr Agnew is chairman of London Insurance Market Investment Trust, the
largest of the new corporate capital groups at Lloyd's.
This year 25 corporate vehicles are underwriting about Pounds 1.6bn of
premiums out of the market's total capacity of Pounds 10.9bn. Both the
number of corporate vehicles and amount of capital underwritten by corporate
representatives are expected to rise next year.
An important hurdle will be the application for stock-market listings of
'dedicated' funds, which provide capital for a narrow range of syndicates.
So far listed funds have been investment trusts supporting a range of
agencies and the syndicates they manage.
Mr Agnew, former group chief executive at Kleinwort Benson, the merchant
bank, stressed the importance of a 'diversity' of capital at Lloyd's -
including from non-corporate members.
Elections for five other places on the council are being contested.
</TEXT>
