<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Hints of cut in M-way
spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dr Brian Mawhinney, the transport secretary, yesterday called for a new
debate on the future of roadbuilding in Britain amid signs that the
government is preparing to curtail spending on trunk roads and motorways.
In his first speech as a minister to a Conservative party conference, Dr
Mawhinney gave a clear indication that he is reassessing the annual Pounds
2bn road-building programme he inherited from his predecessor, Mr John
MacGregor.
He spelled out his commitment to 'manage the existing road work in the most
effective manner', and to minimise new trunk-road building through open
countryside and cities.
He also announced a range of measures to combat car pollution including the
introduction of tougher emission standards for diesel vehicle emission and
random spot checks on polluting vehicles in major cities.
'People are worried about the effect road schemes have on the landscape,
historic sites, woodlands and on wildlife,' he told the conference. 'Part of
our response is to carry out environmental assessments of all road schemes.'
Talking to journalists yesterday, the transport secretary said he was
undertaking a reassessment of the future of roadbuilding. 'I have started to
ask a few questions about the programmes I have inherited. We are now going
to enter a debate as we seek to find a balance between the economic, social
and environmental criteria of road building policy.'
On rail policy, Dr Mawhinney gave the first confirmation since the end of
the rail strike that the government would press ahead with the privatisation
of Railtrack.
'Our country needs a modern and efficient railway,' he told delegates. 'As
with every privatisation, this will improve efficiency, free up investment,
enhance services that the customer wants and expand choice.'
He was warmly applauded by delegates after announcing that driving licences
will carry photographs from July 1996. He said that some 85 per cent of
respondents to a recent consultation exercise had approved the idea.
Rail rules, Page 15
