<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Farm tenancies to be
revived
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to legislate to revive the market in farm tenancies and
provide more opportunities for the start of new farming enterprises.
Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture minister, said a bill would be launched
early in the parliamentary session which opens next month freeing new
tenancies from the succession obligations imposed by the last Labour
government.
Mr Waldegrave described the 1976 legislation, which gave new rights to the
children of tenants, as arguably the most damaging measure this century to
young farmers and new entrants to farming.
Mr Waldegrave said the new legislation would permit farmers and landowners
to 'make agreements to suit each other'. The government had acted in
response to representations by the National Farmers' Union, the Country
Landowners' Association, the Tenant Farmers' Association and young farmers.
He said 'both sides' agreed that the new legislation would result in more
tenant farms becoming available, attract 'new blood' and offer a chance of
reversing the decline in the tenanted family farm.
Responding to attacks by a succession of constituency representatives on the
scale of fraud and corruption in the Common Agricultural Policy, he promised
that Britain would make reform 'central' to future developments in the
European Union.
</TEXT>
