<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Lamont says it may be
necessary to pull out of EU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain should consider leaving the European Union if it cannot halt the
process of European political integration, Mr Norman Lamont, the former
chancellor, said yesterday as Europe dominated the first day of the Tory
conference.
In a hard-hitting speech to an audience of rightwingers on the conference
fringe, Mr Lamont said it was 'simplistic' to say that the option of leaving
the EU was 'unthinkable'.
But he stressed he was not suggesting that Britain should 'today
unilaterally withdraw from Europe'. In an interview, he said he would
advocate withdrawing 'if we cannot get the sort of political deal I think we
deserve and ought to stand for'.
But Lord Tebbit, former Conservative chairman, shouted down rightwing
hecklers' demands to withdraw from Europe at a separate fringe meeting,
saying: 'There's no need to get out. We have the weight to make a difference
if we have the will.'
Lord Tebbit said he had little doubt that Britain could deal 'a fatal blow'
to those seeking to create a European superstate if it made plain it would
veto plans for a political union with the continental powers.
He said enlargement of the EU would require a 'massive change' from the
'centralised Europe of Maastricht' to 'a Gaullist Europe of nation-states,
some of whom may wish to integrate, others of whom may wish to
disintegrate'.
'Those states should be bound by treaty to do at supranational level only
that which is necessary to ensure the free movement of goods, services and
capital.'
Mr William Cash, the Eurosceptic Tory MP for Stafford, urged the government
to 'force the issue' of a single European currency by saying ''No' now' to
any such step.
Mr Lamont, describing the outcome of the Maastricht negotiations as 'a sort
of Band-aid to our problems', said one possible course of action would be
for Britain to say at the intergovernmental conference in 1996 that 'we do
not want to participate in any further political development in Europe'.
The IGC would force Britain to make 'a fundamental choice' over whether to
subscribe to a Europe with a 'federal character,' he said.
'Being part of a federal Europe is not what the British people or the
Conservative party want . . . Britain is on a collision course with its
partners unless we can find a means of resolving the different aspirations.'
He could not, he said, pinpoint 'a single concrete economic advantage that
unambiguously comes to this country because of our membership of the
European Union.'
Mr Lamont added: 'It is a tremendous opportunity now that Tony Blair has
committed himself uncritically to a single European currency, to a more
centralised Europe.
'I believe we should exploit this and home in on a much more distinctive
Conservative European policies.'
</TEXT>
