<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 94 / Gummer to brush aside 'Nimbys'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, environ-ment secretary, yesterday promised to sweep aside
unreasonable objections to new roads and housing and other developments
needed to strengthen the economy, Ivor Owen writes.
He told a fringe meeting the Nimby (not in my backyard) attitudes of those
who oppose any development in their area whatever its merits derived from an
antagonistic view of growth and a misunderstanding of the nature of
conservation.
'Nimbyism describes an obsession with the bric-a-brac of the past and the
substitution of preservation for conservation.' Mr Gummer said this approach
would be rejected whenever it appeared, whether houses, businesses or roads
were the target.
He sympathised with those miscast as Nimbys when they had legitimate
objections to inappropriate development. They were rightly concerned about
intrusive buildings which made no pretence of being an integral part of a
town or village, or when they saw the same designs and materials used in
towns with widely differing characteristics.
</TEXT>
